	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p>To the Editor of the Occident.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Sir.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I notice in your <date>December</date> No<lb/> that you charge the <persName>Rev Solomon Jacobs</persName> with giving<lb/> &#8220;<hi rend="underline">paraphrase</hi>&#8221; which means to translate <hi rend="underline">freely</hi>&#44; not <hi rend="underline">literally</hi>&#44; instead of &#8220;<hi rend="underline">translation</hi>&#8221;<lb/> which is directly opposed to &#8220;<hi rend="underline">paraphrase</hi>&#44;&#8221; in the rendering of<lb/> Exodus 3. 14 <add>Hebrew</add>.  In the Charity Sermon<lb/> which that Gentleman preached in this City&#44; he gave the<lb/> following as the <hi rend="underline">True</hi> and <hi rend="underline">Literal</hi> version of this passage.</p>
				<p>&#8220;I will be unto them now that which I will be unto them hereafter.&#8221;</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">see &#124;Published Sermon.&#124;</p>
				<p>The <persName>Rev Mr Jacobs</persName> bears the reputation in this city of<lb/> being a profound Hebrew Scholar&#44; therefore I think you<lb/> have been rather hasty in preferring a charge which<lb/> involves an ignorance of the Grammatical construction<lb/> of the Hebrew Language.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Truth&#44; being the great &#8220;end&#8221; of all property conducted<lb/> <sic>controversey</sic>&#44; you will best subserve that end by producing<lb/> <hi rend="underline">authorities</hi> to support <del>your</del> the simple assertion<lb/> you have made in the premises&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">an old Subscriber</persName></p>
				<p><placeName>Charleston S.C.</placeName></p>
				<p><date>December. 5613</date>.</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>My dear <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It is the general opinion of those who<lb/> prefer to be your friends&#44; and mine also&#44; that you<lb/> should give some elucidation to the position in which<lb/> you are pleased the better to enable you to do so I<lb/> have addressed the enclosed comment to the Ed of Occ&#44;&#8212;<lb/> you can reply to this without noticing <persName>Mr. Is.</persName> letter at all<lb/> as this comn of mine may be dated <del>early</del> in <date>Dec.</date>&#44; but too<lb/> late for Insertion for <date>Jany.</date>  Simply give the reply as<lb/> I wrote you last.  All the authorities for translation under<lb/> that particular caption&#44; and so with the paraphrases&#58;<lb/> as many as possible&#44; I have worded it so that your<lb/> reply must expose <hi rend="underline"><persName>Is.</persName> ignorance</hi>&#58; which is as much<lb/> as you want to do all his assertions and personalities in the<lb/> bargain notwithstanding&#8221;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The following vein of the subject you perhaps have not thought of.<lb/>  <persName>Jacobs</persName> <hi rend="underline">preaches</hi> this sermon to a large audience&#44; and makes<lb/> use of course of the same words&#8212;calling into question the <hi rend="underline">C<add>&#63;</add></hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">of the Nulgate</hi>&#44; and giving <hi rend="underline">a true and literal</hi> version his audience give him<lb/> <hi rend="underline">credit</hi> for <hi rend="underline">great erudition</hi> and <hi rend="underline">keenners of perception</hi> &#38;c &#38;c during the preaching<lb/> he <hi rend="underline">never mentions &#8220;<persName>Rashi</persName>&#8221;</hi>.  The audience think it his own&#44;<lb/> he publishes it also without giving it as from &#8220;<persName>Rashi</persName>&#44;&#8221; but as soon as the<lb/> <sic>plagarism</sic> is nailed on the head&#44; lo and behold it is not<lb/> his&#44; they are the <hi rend="underline">words of <persName>Rashi</persName></hi>&#44; which <hi rend="underline">are not <persName>Rashis</persName></hi>.<lb/>  Why did he not tell the congregation so and not obtain from<lb/> them a surreptitious reputation for learning <del>which he to</del></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have copied <persName>Bernheims</persName> letter which is enclosed.  I have<lb/> not been able to see this Sent yet.  I most likely will<lb/> tomorrow.</p>
				<p>NB. If he had fancied or had known Aba<add>&#63;</add> or<lb/> Saadial <add>&#63;</add>pulation&#44; and had adduced those instead<lb/> of <persName>Rashi</persName>&#8212;of course a different mode of reasoning to<lb/> suit the several views would have been the result&#44; but<lb/> I do firmly believe he never saw any other great sources of<lb/> information than <persName>Mendlesons</persName> Bible&#44; with Targam&#44; <persName>Beor</persName><lb/> <persName>Rashi</persName> and Medrach.&#8212;which are all he quotes&#44; and<lb/> those not all correct.&#8212;vis <persName>Rashi</persName>.&#8212;&#38; Medrach&#44;&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have no time for more I am sleepy</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Yours Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author"><hi rend="underline">Solomon</hi></persName></p>
				<p><date>Tuesday</date> night 11 &#189; o ck</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><date>4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Jun 1852</date></p>
				<p>I wrote you the day before I got your last letter.</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Editor Occident</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>371 Walnut St</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
		</body>
